surveys.narrative: LARGE POPULATIONS OF BULLHEADS ARE MAKING TROUT FISHING DIFFICULT AT TIMES. SEVERAL FISHERMEN HAVE EXPRESSED CONCERN ABOUT THE BULLHEAD PROBLEM IN DIAMOND LAKE. MOST FISHERMEN STILL ENJOY THE QUALITY OF TROUT THAT ARE CAUGHT ESPECIALLY EARLY IN THE YEAR.THE FISH POPULATION OF DIAMOND IS MADE UP OF RAINBOW TROUT, BULLHEADS, AND MUSKELLUNGE (SHP). THE NETTING ASSESSMENT INDICATES AN EXTREMELY LARGE POPULATION OF BLACK BULLHEADS, AN EXCELLENT POPULATION OF RAINBOW TROUT, AND SOME MUSKELLUNGE. THE LENGTH FREQUENCY INDICATES THAT NUMEROUS STOCKINGS OF RAINBOW TROUT HAVE BEEN SUCCESSFUL. THE BULLHEADS ARE SMALL, POSSIBLY STUNTED, AND DO POSE A PROBLEM FOR THE RAINBOW TROUT FISHERMEN. THE POPULATION OF MUSKELLUNGE PROBABLY WAS CREATED BY FISH THAT HAD ESCAPED FROM GRASSY (BLUEBILL) REARING POND. THE SMALLER OF THE TWO MUSKELLUNGE WAS DETERMINED TO BE 3+ YEARS OLD. THIS INDICATES THAT NATURAL REPRODUCTION HAS OCCURED SINCE GRASSY HAS NOT BEEN USED AS A REARING POND FOR MUSKELLUNGE IN OVER SIX YEARS.

A TOTAL OF 69 RAINBOW TROUT (34.5/SET) (6.95/SET) WERE CAPTURED DURING THE 1991 SURVEY. THIS WAS SOMEWHAT COMPARABLE TO 18/SET - 8.88 POUNDS/SET IN THE 1987 SURVEY. LENGTH FREQUENCY DISTRIBUTION FROM THE 1991 SURVEY RANGE FROM 6.5-14 INCHES, COMPARED TO 5.5-16 INCHES IN 1987. RAINBOW TROUT GROWTH RATES FROM THE 1991 SURVEY WERE ABOUT AVERAGE AT I (5.93) II (8.67) AND III (10.93). OTHER SPECIES CAPTURED DURING THE 1991 SURVEY WERE MUSKELLUNGE, BROWN BULLHEAD AND WALLEYE.MUSKELLUNGE (SHOE PAC STRAIN) WERE ACCIDENTLY INTRODUCED INTO DIAMOND LAKE FROM BLUEBILL LAKE, WHICH WAS BEING USED AS A MUSKY REARING POND. THIS TOOK PLACE WHEN A CULVERT WITH STOP LOGS FAILED TO PREVENT MUSKY FROM ESCAPING INTO DIAMOND LAKE. THIS WAS THE LAST YEAR BLUEBILL LAKE WAS USED AS A MUSKY REARING POND (1981). ANGING TECHNIQUES AND VISUAL OBSERVATIONS SHOW US THERE IS NOW NATURAL REPRODUCTION OF MUSKELLUNGE IN DIAMOND LAKE. AGE AND GROWTH OF MUSKELLUNGE CAPTURED IN 1991 WERE III (12.85") IV (21.7") AND V (28.8"). BULLHEAD NUMBERS WERE DOWN FROM 51.5/SET IN 1987 TO 6/SET IN 1991.ONE WALLEYE (WAE) WAS CAPTURED - 22" (4.8 POUNDS) AND WAS PROBABLY INTRODUCED LIKE MUSKELLUNGE WHEN BLUEBILL LAKE WAS USED AS A WALLEYE REARING POND.

Diamond Lake is one of five designated stream-trout lakes in the Walker area. Other stream-trout lakes in the Walker Management Area are Hazel, Perch, Teepee, and Willard Lakes. Diamond Lake was first used as a stream-trout lake in 1967. The trout population in Diamond Lake depends upon stocking because rainbow trout do not naturally reproduce in this lake. The lake was chemically treated in 1998 to remove competing fish species, so that rainbow trout stocking could be resumed. Since the reclamation, five year-classes of rainbow trout have been stocked and four year-classes were sampled during 2003. Sixty rainbow trout were sampled in 2003. The average length of sampled rainbow trout was 12 inches, and fish up to 17 inches were sampled.Since 1998, Fisheries personnel have been sampling zooplankton, the tiny animals on which Diamond Lake rainbow trout feed. The quantity of zooplankton available in Diamond Lake is highest among the five designated stream-trout lakes. Also, Diamond Lake has the best rainbow trout fishery among the five lakes.

Diamond Lake is one of five designated stream-trout lakes in the Walker area. Other stream-trout lakes in the Walker area are Hazel, Perch, Teepee, and Willard. Diamond Lake was first used as a stream-trout lake in 1967. The lake was rehabilitated in 1998 to remove competing fish species, so that rainbow trout stocking could be resumed. Since the reclamation, two year classes of rainbow trout have been stocked. Ninety-one rainbow trout were sampled in 2000. The average length of sampled rainbow trout was 10.3 inches, and fish up to 14 inches were sampled.

Diamond Lake is one of five designated stream-trout lakes in the Walker area. Other stream-trout lakes in the Walker area are Hazel, Perch, Teepee, and Willard. Diamond Lake was first used as a stream-trout lake in 1967. The lake was rehabilitated in 1998 to remove competing fish species, so that rainbow trout stocking could be resumed. Since the reclamation, four year-classes of rainbow trout have been stocked. Seventy-two rainbow trout were sampled in 2002 with two gill nets. The average length of sampled rainbow trout was 12 inches, and fish up to 17 inches were sampled.

Diamond Lake (DOW# 11 396; Lake Class 29) has a total surface area of 82 acres, a shoreline length of 1.86 miles, and a maximum depth of 31 feet. A public access owned by the US Forest Service is located on the west shore. Diamond Lake offers excellent Rainbow Trout fishing in a remote, wilderness like setting. The lake is totally within the Chippewa National Forest and the shoreline is undeveloped. Diamond Lake is one of four designated stream trout lakes in the Walker Management Area. Other stream trout lakes in the Walker Management Area are Hazel, Perch, and Teepee.

Diamond Lake was first used as a stream trout lake in 1967. Rainbow Trout do not reproduce in this lake and the population is instead supported entirely by stocking to provide unique angling opportunities. The average length of Rainbow Trout sampled in gill nets in 2013 was 12 inches and lengths ranged from 9 to19 inches. Historically, Rainbow Trout up to 17 inches in length have been sampled in several previous assessments, but the 19-inch Rainbow Trout sampled in 2013 was the largest ever. Anglers will have excellent opportunities to catch rainbows over 15 inches in length during the 2014 season. The lake was chemically treated in October of 2008 to remove competing fish species, specifically Black Crappie, presumed to have been illegally introduced by anglers. These fish eventually overpopulated and stunted, reducing the recreational value of the Rainbow Trout fishery and prompting a costly reclamation process. Yearling Rainbow Trout were stocked in May 2009 and annual stocking of fingerling Rainbow Trout was resumed in the fall of 2009. Excellent Rainbow Trout fishing followed the 2008 reclamation and should continue in future years, provided stocking is maintained.

People can have significant impacts on lakes and the fish populations they support. Harvest, lakeshore development, removal of shoreline vegetation, and introductions of invasive species can all adversely affect fish populations. Currently not aquatic invasive species (AIS) have been identified in Diamond Lake. AIS are moved from infested to non-infested waters by anglers, boaters, and lake shore owners and can adversely impact lakes and fish populations. To avoid spreading AIS, lake users are required to remove all aquatic plants or animals from their watercraft and drain all water from their boat before leaving the access. If you suspect an infestation of an invasive species in this lake, save a specimen and report it to a local natural resource office. Additional information on all of these topics can be found on the DNR website (www.dnr.state.mn.us) or by contacting the Walker Area Fisheries office.

Diamond Lake is one of five designated stream-trout lakes in the Walker Management Area. Other stream-trout lakes in the Walker Management Area are Hazel, Perch, Teepee, and Willard Lakes.

Diamond Lake was first used as a stream-trout lake in 1967. The trout population in Diamond Lake depends upon stocking because rainbow trout do not naturally reproduce in this lake. The lake is stocked each fall with rainbow trout. In 2006, the average length of sampled rainbow trout was 9 inches, and fish up to 12 inches were present. Trout abundance in 2006 was similar to 2004 and 2005, but lower than abundance in 2000, 2002 and 2003.

This lake was chemically treated in 1998 to remove competing fish species, so that rainbow trout stocking could be resumed. However, black crappie were first sampled in 2004, have been found each year since then, and have become very abundant. This species was not known to exist in the lake prior to the 1998 reclamation, and it appears someone introduced them after the reclamation. Black crappie lengths ranged from about 3 to 9 inches. Abundance of minnows has decreased since the discovery of black crappie in Diamond Lake.

Diamond Lake (DOW# 11-396; Lake Class 29) has a total surface area of 82 acres, a shoreline length of 1.86 miles, and a maximum depth of 31 feet. A public access owned by the US Forest Service is located on the west shore. Diamond Lake offers good rainbow trout fishing in a remote, wilderness-like setting. The lake is totally within the Chippewa National Forest and the shoreline is undeveloped. Diamond Lake is one of five designated stream-trout lakes in the Walker Management Area. Other stream-trout lakes in the Walker Management Area are Hazel, Perch, and Teepee. Diamond Lake was first used as a stream-trout lake in 1967. The trout population in Diamond Lake depends upon stocking because rainbow trout do not naturally reproduce in this lake.

The average length of rainbow trout sampled in 2008 was 8 inches, and fish up to 13 inches were present. Historically, rainbow trout up to 17 inches in length have been sampled in several previous assessments. The lake was chemically treated in 1998 to remove competing fish species, so that rainbow trout stocking could be resumed. Excellent fishing followed this reclamation. However, black crappies were sampled in 2004. Rainbow trout numbers and average size declined as black crappie numbers increased. Black crappies were not known to exist in the lake prior to the 1998 reclamation. In order to restore the quality rainbow trout fishery, Diamond Lake was reclaimed again in October of 2008 using rotenone, a fish toxicant, to kill all fish present in the lake. Spring stocking of yearling rainbow trout is scheduled for May of 2009 to provide angling opportunities during the 2009 season. Fall rainbow trout fingerling stocking is scheduled to resume in the fall of 2009. Anglers are asked to refrain from introducing fish into Diamond Lake.

Diamond Lake (DOW# 11-0396; Lake Class 29) is a 77-acre lake located near Hackensack, MN. There is a US Forest Service public access located on the west shore. Diamond Lake has a shoreline length of 1.86 miles and a maximum depth of 31 feet. Diamond Lake offers excellent Rainbow Trout fishing in a remote, wilderness like setting. The lake is entirely within the Chippewa National Forest and the shoreline is undeveloped. Diamond Lake is one of four designated stream trout lakes in the Walker Fisheries Management Area. Other stream trout lakes in the Walker Management Area are Hazel, Perch, and Teepee Lakes.

Diamond Lake was first used as a stream trout lake in 1967. Rainbow Trout do not reproduce in this lake and the population is supported entirely by stocking to provide a unique angling opportunity. The average length of Rainbow Trout sampled in in 2017 was 12 inches and lengths ranged from 8 to 20 inches. Historically, Diamond has produced several fish larger than 15 inches. The 2017 sample produced eight fish over 15 inches in length. Nine of ten fish greater than 14 inches long were Kamloops strain. The lake was chemically treated in October of 2008 to remove competing fish species. Excellent Rainbow Trout fishing followed the 2008 reclamation and should continue, provided stocking is maintained and other species are not introduced. 14,000 Arlee strain Rainbow Trout fingerlings are stocked annually in the fall. In the springs 2014 and 2015, yearling Kamloops strain Rainbow Trout were stocked in addition to fall fingerling stocking. All Kamloops strain fish that were stocked in 2014 and 2015 had an adipose fin clip for identification. Black Bullhead were first sampled in 2013. So far, the Rainbow Trout fishery remains excellent. In January 2015 Diamond Lake was opened to winter Trout fishing for the first time and provided increased opportunities for Trout anglers in the Walker area. Based on two years of sampling after winter ice fishing opened on Diamond Lake in 2015, there are no indications that winter ice fishing has had an effect on Rainbow Trout sizes or abundance.
